        <name>23.5.2.2 ex2 sine series</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
Obtain the half-range Fourier Sine series for the functions
\[f(t) =&amp;nbsp; t \hspace{1cm} 0 \leq t \leq 1 \]
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Series is
&lt;p&gt;\( \displaystyle{ \sum_{n=1}^\infty} \) [[input:ans1]]&lt;/p&gt;
[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&amp;nbsp;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>We extend as an odd function, so 
\[ f(t) = -t \hspace{1cm} -1 \leq t \leq 0 \]
Therefore we define 
\[ F(t) = 
\begin{cases} 
-t \hspace{1cm} -1 \leq t \leq 0 \\
t \hspace{1.2cm} 0 \leq t \leq 1
\end{cases}
\]
As \( F(t)\) is an odd function, \(a_n = 0\). Then we have
\[
\begin{align}
b_n &amp;amp;= \int_{-1}^1 F(t) \sin n\pi t \hspace{0.1cm} dt = 2 \int_{0}^1  t \sin n\pi t \hspace{0.1cm} dt  \\
&amp;amp;= 2\left[ - \dfrac{ t }{n\pi} \cos n\pi t \right]_0^1 + \dfrac{1}{n\pi} \int _0^1 \cos n\pi t \hspace{0.1cm} dt \\
&amp;amp;= -\dfrac{2}{n\pi} \cos n\pi \\
&amp;amp;= -\dfrac{2}{n\pi} (-1)^n
\end{align}
\]
So the half range Fourier sine series is given by
\[ F(t) =\sum_{n=1}^\infty -\dfrac{2}{n\pi} (-1)^n \sin n\pi t \]</generalfeedback>
